Find all solutions to the equation below:

\[5 (x-{10})^2+12~=~137\]

\[5 (x-{10})^2+12~=~137\]

First, subtract 12 from both sides.

\[5 (x-{10})^2~=~125\]

Second, divide both sides by 5.

\[(x-{10})^2~=~25\]

Undo the squaring. Remember the plus-minus symbol!

\[x-{10}~=~\pm5\]

Add 10 to both sides.

\[x~=~10\pm5\]

So the two solutions are \(x=15\) and \(x=5\).

By completing the square, find both solutions to the given equation:

\[x^2-12x~=~64\]

The given equation:

\[x^2-12x~=~64\]

In order to make the left side of the equation a perfect square, we can add \(\left(\frac{-12}{2}\right)^2=36\) to both sides (where -12 is the linear coefficient).

\[x^2-12x+36~=~64+36\]

\[x^2-12x+36~=~100\]

We can rewrite the left side in factored form. Notice that because the left side is a perfect square, we get a squared binomial.

\[(x-6)^2~=~100\]

Because the squaring function is not one-to-one, when we "undo" it in algebra, we need to consider the possibility of multiple solutions. In this case both 10 and -10 produce 100 when squared.

\[x-6~=~\pm 10\]

And, lastly, subtract -6 from both sides of the equation.

\[x~=~6\pm10\]

\[x~=~16~~~~~~~~\text{or}~~~~~~~~x~=~-4\]

Quadratic polynomial \(p\) is defined below in standard form. \[p(x)~=~{2}x^{2}-{8}x+{5}\]

By completing the square, you can rewrite the quadratic polynomial in vertex form:

\[p(x) = a(x-h)^2+k\]

where \((h,k)\) is the vertex of the parabola. Determine the coordinates of the vertex of quadratic polynomial \(p\).

  • \(h=\)
  • \(k=\)

We are given \(p(x)~=~{2}x^{2}-{8}x+{5}\). From the first two terms, factor out 2.

\[p(x)~=~2\left(x^{2}-{4}x\right)+{5}\]

Determine the constant needed to complete the square (of the expression inside parentheses) by dividing the linear coefficient by 2 and then squaring the result. \(\left(\frac{-4}{2}\right)^2 ~=~ \left(-2\right)^2 ~=~ 4\). Add and subtract this amount inside the parentheses.

\[p(x)~=~2\left(x^{2}-{4}x+{4}-{4}\right)+{5}\]

Notice the first three terms inside the parentheses are a perfect square. Rewrite them in factored form.

\[p(x)~=~2\left(\left(x-{2}\right)^2-4\right)+{5}\]

Distribute the 2.

\[p(x)~=~2\left(x-{2}\right)^2-8+{5}\]

Combine the constants.

\[p(x)~=~2\left(x-{2}\right)^2 -{3}\]

And so:

\[h = 2\] \[k = -3\]


Quadratic polynomial \(p\) is defined below in standard form. \[p(x)~=~{5}x^{2}+{90}x+{411}\]

By completing the square, you can rewrite the quadratic polynomial in vertex form:

\[p(x) = a(x-h)^2+k\]

where \((h,k)\) is the vertex of the parabola. Determine the coordinates of the vertex of quadratic polynomial \(p\).

  • \(h=\)
  • \(k=\)

We are given \(p(x)~=~{5}x^{2}+{90}x+{411}\). From the first two terms, factor out 5.

\[p(x)~=~5\left(x^{2}+{18}x\right)+{411}\]

Determine the constant needed to complete the square (of the expression inside parentheses) by dividing the linear coefficient by 2 and then squaring the result. \(\left(\frac{18}{2}\right)^2 ~=~ \left(9\right)^2 ~=~ 81\). Add and subtract this amount inside the parentheses.

\[p(x)~=~5\left(x^{2}+{18}x+{81}-{81}\right)+{411}\]

Notice the first three terms inside the parentheses are a perfect square. Rewrite them in factored form.

\[p(x)~=~5\left(\left(x+{9}\right)^2-81\right)+{411}\]

Distribute the 5.

\[p(x)~=~5\left(x+{9}\right)^2-405+{411}\]

Combine the constants.

\[p(x)~=~5\left(x+{9}\right)^2 +{6}\]

And so:

\[h = -9\] \[k = 6\]
